{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Gregory Currie produced the first comprehensive philosophy of film in the analytic tradition with Image and Mind in 1995, and identified the essence of film as 'moving pictures' (Currie, 1997, p. 47).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "His ontology of film is strictly realist, and he rejects both cognitive and perceptual illusionism in film.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "In cognitive or strong illusionism the viewer believes that she occupies the position of the camera, and is therefore present in the story.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Currie correctly notes that audiences neither react nor think in this way, and dismisses the 'Imagined Observer Hypothesis' (Currie, 1995, p. 167).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "In perceptual or weak illusionism, cinematic experience represents the world in a particular way, even though the viewer knows this to be false, and the thesis is that the movement of images onscreen is illusory in this sense.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Currie's rejection of this claim is highly controversial, with both illusionists and realists appealing to an intuitive view of cinematic motion.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Kania agrees with Currie that there is no illusion of physical objects in motion onscreen, but rejects his alternative of a veridical experience of images in motion.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "An obvious third possibility is that we have an illusion of images moving in front of us (Kania, 2002, p. 252).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Ponech identifies the essence of the debate as being 'whether the image undergoes objective displacement, that is, moves continuously in a contiguous space, independent of any perceptual uptake' (Ponech, 2006, p. 354).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Ponech differentiates visual displays from display formats, and demonstrates that the former possess two essential properties, pixels and stroboscopic motion.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Singletons are real perceptual objects and their continuous stroboscopic displacement is real movement.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "While Ponech has shown that singletons move in the same way as objects—contiguously in space and time—he cannot show that they exhibit garden-variety motion because they are not objects.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Kania's argument against Currie relies upon a single contention, the connection between the succession of still images that constitute the medium of film, and the perception of the moving images on the screen.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Projection at 24 fps is therefore a necessary condition for the reception of the art form of film by an audience.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The experience of film is the experience of seeing moving images under specific perceptual circumstances (e.g., 24 fps on a white screen in a dark room), which are necessary for the experience.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "If one is considering perception in general, or any particular aspect thereof, the default setting is that humans with fully functioning senses perceive reality rather than illusion.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Currie's theory of cinematic motion is the most plausible of the three options.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
